\subsection{\href{https://beta.lmfdb.org/knowledge/show/ag.variety}{Algebraic variety }}
\begin{definition}\label{ag.variety}
\uses{ag.affine_space,ag.projective_space,ring.field,ring.prime_ideal}
There are two main kinds of \textbf{algebraic varieties}, *affine varieties* and *projective varieties*.   Both are defined as the set of common zeros of a collection of polynomials.
Let $K$ be a \hyperref[ring.field]{field} with algebraic closure $\overline{K}$.

An \textbf{affine algebraic set} is a subset of \hyperref[ag.affine_space]{affine space} $\mathbb A^n(\overline K)$ of the form
$$ V(I) = \{P \in \mathbb A^n(\overline K) : f(P) = 0\text{ for all }f \in I\} $$
where $I \subseteq \overline{K}[x_1,\dots,x_n]$ is an ideal.  Given an affine algebraic set $V$, its \textbf{defining ideal} is
$$ I(V) = \{ f \in \overline{K}[x_1,\dots,x_n] : f(P)=0\text{ for all }P \in V\}.$$

An \textbf{affine variety} over $\overline{K}$ is an affine algebraic set whose defining ideal $I \subseteq \overline{K}[x_1,\dots,x_n]$ is a \hyperref[ring.prime_ideal]{prime ideal}.  An \textbf{affine variety} over $K$ is an affine variety over $\overline{K}$ whose defining ideal can be generated by polynomials in $K[x_1,\dots,x_n]$.

We define projective notions similarly.  A \textbf{projective algebraic set} is a subset of \hyperref[ag.projective_space]{projective space} $\mathbb P^n(\overline{K})$ defined by a *homogeneous* ideal $I \subseteq \overline{K}[x_1,\dots,x_n]$.  A \textbf{projective variety} over $\overline{K}$ is a projective algebraic set whose defining ideal is a homogeneous \hyperref[ring.prime_ideal]{prime ideal}.  A \textbf{projective variety} over $K$ is a projective variety over $\overline{K}$ whose defining ideal can be generated by homogeneous polynomials in $K[x_1,\dots,x_n]$.
\end{definition}
